result.execSummary:
The defendant William G Duncan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:00 a.m. - Defendant, William G Duncan, in custody, appeared.  Prosecuting attorney Andrea Nodolf in court.  Jenae Brantner and Paul Gilbertson in court.   Renee McDonald - clerk
This hearing is set as a review.  Attorney Nodolf states that there is an agreement.   William Duncan states he is waiving his right to have an attorney with him today.   Nodolf called Jenae Brantner and she testifies.   Jenae has been working with Defendant since January 2018.  Most recently the Defendant absconded.  Jenae met with the Defendant and initially he did not want to remain in the program but now chooses to continue the plan.   States that the agreement is that 12 days of his sentence is to be lifted as he has been incarcerated.  Has an work interview on June 17, 2019 and currently has housing.  Counseling to begin next Tuesday and will be monitored with GPS monitoring through DOC.   Teams recommendation is that the Defendant continue with the program.  William Duncan sworn and testifies.   States he has been in treatment in Black River Falls however it's been a challenge since returning and has violated the treatment court rules.  Believes he can be successful in the program and understands that his behaviors could lead to a termination hearing.   Attorney Nodolf questions the Defendant.   Defendant states the changes he plans to make to be successful.  

COURT -   The court states the expectations of the Defendant.   The plan put in place will be adopted by the treatment court team.  The court expects compliance of the plan.   The 12 days of imposed and stayed jail can be lifted at this time.
